Feb 19 2008 	A Great Find....	Myself, fiance and 20mths old daughter stayed at the Marmara for 4nights - Nov/Dec 2007. After having booked it we were a bit apprehensive due to the mixed reviews. However, when we settled in we were pleasantly surprised.On our arrival there was an issue with our booking but this was sorted out relatively quickly - they had us booked in for only one night, so I suggest that you have a printout of your email confirmation if booking through the website. Due to the mix up meant that we had to change to another apartment on our last day. This was not too problematic as it just meant that we packed a day earlier.The hotel is situated in the upper East Side but subway is just a few blocks away - 5/10 minutes walk. This may put people off as it is not midtown but we did not see it as a concern. Subway easy to use - even with a buggy. Used it everyday to get around the city - cheaper than the cabs. We chose these apartments as we did not want to be in the middle of the hustle and bustle of midtown - wanted somewhere that was quieter - still was busy as hotel situated on an avenue so you will get traffic noise daytime and nightime. You soon get used to the noise and it did not bother our daughter who slept very well!The apartment we stayed in was very spacious - large living area, kitchen/diner, nice bathroom and bedroom. Hotel provided us with a cot for daughter - continental size not travel cot which was ideal. There are lots of places surrounding the hotel that you can buy food/drink - mini-mart across the road where you can get the essentials such as bread, milk etc. Also there is a deli on the corner by the hotel where you can get some nice treats - fruit, yoghurts. There are also a number of restaurants/takeaways in the area - bagel shops, mexicans, italians - opposite the hotel is a restaurant called 'Nick's' - great pizza - the large pizza is enormous!The hotel staff were courteous - not overly friendly but not rude. They always assisted us with any services that we required.Apart from the mixup with our booking, we had a great stay at a great apartment - family friendly with all the amenities that you require. Would recommend this hotel to family and friends and would stay here again.	
Jan 4 2008 	Good base for family holiday	I stayed at the Marmara for 10 days over Christmas 2007 with my wife and young son (18 months). Having stayed in typical mid town tourist hotels in NYC before, we wanted more space and a quieter neighborhood than the usual Manhattan experience and the Marmara delivered this very well.As with most hotels it is not quite what the website suggests - it is modern but not contemporary or designer in any sense. However our apartment with separate bedroom, living room, kitchen and bathroom was clean, spacious and well equipped. The daily maid service was excellent.The local area is residential with good restaurants and shops. Being out of the usual tourist area of midtown, we met many friendly New Yorkers, were welcomed to all the diners and restaurants we visited and enjoyed walking to Central Park and many children's playgrounds. We found that we could walk to many locations, stopping for coffee on the way and take cabs home at the end of a tiring day!The Marmara is not a conventional tourist hotel with no bar, restaurant or concierge. We found the staff efficient rather than friendly so if you are a 'needy' guest, you may want to go elsewhere. However if you want to experience living in NYC rather than just visiting it, I'd consider staying here. I would certainly go here again.	
Nov 23 2007 	Short Term Stay	We arrived at our room and the staff were very helpful. We never had any issues with the hotel or staff however we only stayed for three nights. I was apprehensive about booking this hotel for a short term stay but it ended up being perfect. The subway was only a couple of blocks away on 96th and Lex. Lots of little restaurants around the area. I would agree with another reviewer that there was construction outside that began earlier in the morning (around 6am) but it's NYC, what do you expect? If you are interested in staying in a neighborhood close to the nearby tourist attractions - I would not recommend this hotel. We were visiting a friend on 95th and 3rd ave, so it worked out perfectly for us. The kitchen was more than adequate, and the nearby Gristede's market saved us so much money!!	
Nov 21 2007 	Not a good stay!!	While the room in itself was ok, very large as I had a one bedroom suite with a kitchen. Descent furnishings. The level of service was horrible. If I could take the hotel and move it to a better location and change the staff I would stay there again but since that is not happening I will NOT be returning to the Marmara and I visit New York a lot.The hotel staff was very disinterested in helping with any kind of problems other then the one night I could not get the sofa bed to work, they pretty much ignored me.The room I was given was on the 3rd floor and right off of a busy street that was under construction. When I reserved the room I specifically requested a high floor where it was quiet. The rooms have large windows which would be nice if the view wasn't of the very loud construction going on.I asked repeatedly to be moved but my requests were ignored. I was very busy during my 6 night stay and by the time I got back to my room, which was in the early am, I just wanted to sleep in a bit but it was impossible.Also upon check out there were multiple phone calls charges to my room. No one ever used the phone as me and my guest have cell phones that fit all of our calling needs. The ladies were rude about it when I told them that I did NOT call Turkey for $28 the day I checked in, in fact the time it said the call was made I was asleep. They kept accusing me or my guest of making these calls but my guest did not even arrive until the next day after the call was made. They said they would investigate the calls and get back to me but they have yet to do so. There were also 4 other calls that were not placed from my room for .52 cents but I wasn't about to argue with these ladies over such an amount as I had a plane to catch. They also spoke to each other in their native language in front of me, about me which I found very rude.I have never been treated so badly by the front desk staff. During my stay they were very disinterested to say the least.Also the location is pretty far from most of the sight seeing areas, Broadway, Times Square, ect and the cab drivers liked to take the long way so the cost for taxi's very pretty expensive. I should have just paid a bit more and stayed closer to midtown.Now that I am home I am completely exhausted. If you do choose to stay here make sure you check your bill before you check out. Something very fishy is going on.	
Jul 26 2007 	Below average hotel	After doing a long and through research on many websites including reading the reviews on tripadvisor, I booked a week at Marmara Manhattan on their website. Our problems were:1)Hotel site shows a roof top terrace with sweeping views- It was closed and under construction for a penthouse and there was no mention of it on the website, at the hotel, during the check in. Even after I brought it up, they brushed it off. Even though this was one of the main reasons I booked this hotel.2)Hotel site says suites have queen size beds, and nice views- Our suite had a full size bed, and view was well the small building across the street.3)Hotel site says that the quieter upper east side. There was a construction at the hotel, outside, and outside of our window crews were there. We asked for a quieter room, and we were told they would check- 3 DAYS later which was the day before we were due to leave, they said NO ROOMS and NO DISCOUNT would be given. 4) Very rude front desk manager, she talks and fights with other guests in front of everyone, she is very unfriendly. She really should learn that customer service starts with a smile, whether one is in NY or wherever. Overall, I travel for work and leisure extensively, used to live in NY for 3 years, this is one of the worst places to stay in NYC, due to their arrogant, unaccomodating, higher than thou attitude and false advertisement.The only plus, rooms are clean.	
Jun 1 2007 	Good accomodation on the Upper East side	We stayed at the Marmara for 8 nights from 8 May 2007. We were two single adults travelling together. We were booked at this property by another Hotel who had reserved this room for us.The room we were given was a 1 bedroom apartment, comprising a king bed and a sofa sleeper in the living area. I used the sofa sleeper which was ok (not brilliant but ok). There were two large TVs in the apartment. The kitchen area had a large (although dated) refrigerator, a gas oven and hob, dishwasher and microwave. Pots and pans were provided although there was only one smallish frying pan and no baking dishes. The apartment had an onsuite bathroom and a separate toilet and basin near the entrance door. The apartment was apparently quite spacious for a NY apartment. We weren't disturbed by neighbour noise, although the aircon did make noise but it wasn't too bad.The building is located close to 2nd ave, and 3 blocks from the nearest subway station. We were comfortable with the 15 min walk to get there. The neighbourhood felt safe. We cooked primarily in the apartment so it was handy to have a largish supermarket a couple of blocks away. On the corner of the Hotel was a small deli which is also worth a visit but a bit more expensive. The Hotel has a laundry on the lower level which was also handy ($1.50 per load). The front desk staff seemed to vary quite a bit. I felt they were efficient but didn't show much emotion and weren't overly helpful with information.In summary I felt this property was quite expensive at around $404 USD per night (not including taxes). We also stayed at the Beacon Hotel on the west side for a few nights which was probably half the rate but not as large or comfortable. I think the Marmara would suit adults rather than families with small children.	
May 23 2007	A terrific Manhattan setting	My wife an I decided to celebrate our tenth wedding anniversary in NYC. We wanted to stay in a relaxing place with the comforts of home in a real Manhattan setting. The Marmara Manhattan exceeded our expectations. Recently transformed from apartment building to hotel the Marmara has preserved the qualities of an apartment building. The suites are large and comfortable with fully equipped kitchens and stylish furnishings. Super comfy bed, a real bonus after a long day of sightseeing. The daily housekeeping service was outstanding, they go the extra mile to keep things clean and tidy. The most enjoyable part of our stay at the Marmara was its charming location. We loved walking the Upper East Side streets to the bus stops, the subway or Central Park . As we strolled we met people walking their children to school, or taking their dogs for a walk, they recommended restaurants or favorite galleries. After a couple of days we felt part of the neighborhood. The hotel does not offer food services but there is a terrific deli next door that has a wide assortment of fresh and prepared foods for take-out or delivery to your suite. There are also a number of restaurants within walking distance of the hotel. To go downtown we often took the bus as it allowed us to see the sights and mingle with the locals. At the end of the day it was very nice to come home to a quieter part of town, very relaxing.	
